{{About|the academic|the drug smuggler|Derrick Gregory}}

{{BLP sources|date=August 2014}}'''Derek Gregory''' [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D. (Cantab)]] [[British Academy|FBA]], [[Royal Society of Canada|FRSC]] (born 1 March 1951) is a British academic and world-renowned [[geography|geographer]] who is currently Peter Wall Distinguished Professor and Professor of Geography at the [[University of British Columbia]] in [[Vancouver]]. He formerly held positions at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.pwias.ubc.ca/people/distinguished-professor/derek-gregory.php |title=Derek Gregory - Peter Wall Institute for Advanced Studies |first= |last= |work=pwias.ubc.ca |year=2013 |accessdate=20 March 2013}}</ref>

Gregory is best known for his book ''[[The Colonial Present: Afghanistan, Palestine and Iraq]]'', published in 2004. This book discusses the actions of Israel, the United States and the United Kingdom in the [[Middle East]] after [[9/11]]. It reflects how the popular [[discourse]]s found in the [[Mass media|media]] and in political circles indicate a continued [[Orientalism]] and [[colonialism]]. It also draws on the work of political theorist [[Giorgio Agamben]] and in particular his theory of the '[[State of Exception (2005)|state of exception]]'.

Earlier works by Gregory have concentrated on [[political geography|political]], [[cultural geography|cultural]] and [[historical geography]]. He has also contributed to theoretical writing on [[Imagined geographies]] and [[David Harvey (geographer)|David Harvey]].  A book published in 1994, ''[[Geographical Imaginations]]'', explores the relations between social theory and place, space and landscape.

He graduated from the University of Cambridge with a [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Master of Arts]] and a Doctor of Philosophy in 1981. He has honorary doctorates from the University of Heidelberg and Roskilde University, and he was awarded the [[Gold Medal (RGS)|Founder's Medal]] of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] in 2006.  His current research is on late modern war and on the cultural/political histories and geographies of bombing.

He blogs at www.geographicalimaginations.com<ref>{{Cite web|title = geographical imaginations|url = http://geographicalimaginations.com/|website = geographical imaginations|access-date = 2016-01-16|language = en-US}}</ref>

