{{Geographer-stub}}

'''Detachment''' ([[Old French]] ''de'', from, and ''[at]tach'', joining with a stake) under [[international law]] is the ''formal'', permanent separation of and loss of [[sovereignty]] over some territory to another geo-political entity (either adjacent or non-contiguous). After World War I [[Alsace]] and [[Lorraine (region)|Lorraine]] were a formal detachment from Germany. More often detachment occurs as a process within a country, for example the creation of the Federal [[District of Columbia]] resulted from a detachment of territory from the State of Maryland. The removal of territory from a city or special district is a detachment.<ref name="Alaska">{{Cite web|title=Detachment from a City Government|publisher=Alaska Division of Community and Regional Affairs|url=http://www.commerce.state.ak.us/dca/logon/muni/muni-citydetach.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110624224251/http://www.commerce.state.ak.us/dca/LOGON/muni/muni-citydetach.htm|archivedate=24 June 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Detachment of Territory|publisher=U.S. Legal, Inc.|url=http://municipal.uslegal.com/change-of-status-and-change-of-boundaries/detachment-of-territory/}}</ref> Within a country detachment is governed by the laws of the supervening entity.<ref name="Alaska" /><ref>{{Cite web |author=Towne, George |year=2003 |title=State Notes: Topics of Legislative Interest: Annexation and Detachment In Michigan |publisher=Senate Fiscal Agency, Michigan State Senate |url=http://www.senate.michigan.gov/sfa/publications%5Cnotes%5C2003notes%5Cnotesmayjun03gt.pdf |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HLrma9Pi?url=http://www.senate.michigan.gov/sfa/publications%5Cnotes%5C2003notes%5Cnotesmayjun03gt.pdf |archivedate=13 June 2013 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>  Detachment can be considered the opposite or reverse of [[annexation]].

==Suez Canal==
The formal detachment of Egypt from the Turkish Empire was a condition for British investment in the Suez Canal.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Lawrence, Thomas Joseph|year=1884|title=The Suez Canal in International Law|journal=The Law Magazine and Review (5th series)|volume=9|pages=117&ndash;143, [https://books.google.com/books?id=b_QwAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA137 page 137]}}</ref>

==League of Nations mandates==
{{Main|League of Nations mandate}}
Following World War I, a number of colonial territories and border territories were detached from Germany, as well as portions of the Austrian-Hungarian Empire and Ottoman Empire being detached. Some of these detachments were incorporated directly into new countries, such as Yugoslavia, or annexed by existing countries such as [[Northern Schleswig]] into Denmark.  But some, particularly in the [[Middle East]] and those of the [[List of former German colonies|German colonies]], were placed under the "protection" of one or another of the [[Allies of World War I|Allied countries]] who won the war, including Germany's concessions in China, [[Kiautschou Bay concession|Kiautschou]] and [[Chefoo#History|Chefoo]]. From a [[rule of law]] standpoint these [[protectorate]]s were not war [[Looting|''booty'']], but "mandates" from a legally constituted international body, so detachment occurred without annexation.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Korman, Sharon|year=1996|title=The Right of Conquest: The Acquisition of Territory by Force in International Law and Practice|location=Oxford, England|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ueDO1dJyjrUC&pg=PA142 142]|isbn=978-0-19-828007-1}}</ref> 


